{"type":"message","id":"89ffe205","parentId":"956eae46","timestamp":"2026-03-23T21:21:16.986Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_skoytfd0fwq9_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-23 171103\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: the (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what single concrete action I should take.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 are marked complete\r\n- Key pending items include:\r\n  1. Write PowerShell wrapper for FocusDecayMemory CLI\r\n  2. Define significance scoring for pulse content\r\n  3. Tune λ empirically\r\n  4. Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n  5. Measure compression ratio\r\n\r\nThe most recent insight is about COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY - the idea that compression and causal discovery are the same problem. The next action is to implement the TIC (Temporal Invariance Compression) experiment.\r\n\r\nThe pending action says:\r\n- [ ] Implement TIC classifier on `logs/pulse_*.md` files\r\n- [ ] Measure invariant/variant classification accuracy\r\n- [ ] Predict next pulse content from invariants\r\n- [ ] Validate against success criteria (>70%, >60%)\r\n\r\nSo my ONE concrete action should be to start implementing the TIC experiment. The most logical first step is to examine the existing pulse logs to understand their structure, then create a basic TIC classifier.\r\n\r\nLet me check what pulse logs exist and what they contain, then create the TIC implementation.\r\n\r\nFirst, I need to observe: what pulse logs exist and what's their structure? This will inform the TIC implementation.\r\n\r\nMy action: Create the TIC classifier script that can:\r\n1. Read pulse logs\r\n2. Identify invariant vs variant content\r\n3. Test classification accuracy\r\n\r\nLet me create a PowerShell script that implements the TIC classifier.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\n